article.headline: Houston shoots just 37 percent from field
article.linkText: Lynx defeat Comets for the third straight time
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Even without Katie Smith, Minnesota's offensive
spark came from behind the arc in its first win at Houston.

Nicole Ohlde scored 16 points and Helen Darling added 14 to lead
the Lynx to a 72-64 win over the Comets on Wednesday night.
Minnesota made 7 of 16 3-pointers to improve to 3-0 against Houston
this season.

Smith, the Lynx leading scorer at 18.8 points per game,
reinjured her right knee at the Athens Olympics and will have
surgery on Friday.

"As a team, everyone had to step up because we didn't have
Katie," Ohlde said. "It was definitely hard to get a rhythm
going, but it was due to the break. We came out in the second half,
found it and got on a roll."

Svetlana Ambrosimova and Tamika Williams each scored 12 points
for the Lynx (16-11).

Sheryl Swoopes scored a game-high 22 points for Houston (12-15)
and Tina Thompson added 19. The Olympic gold medalists could not
help the Comets extend their home winning streak to five games.

With the loss, Houston dropped four games behind the Lynx in the
Western Conference standings.

"I can't remember the last time we gave up 47 points in the
second half," Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "I have no idea
what this loss is going to do for us but it sure does put us in
some kind of hole.

"We are not a very smart basketball team right now. We didn't
defend and we just didn't come to play."

With Houston ahead 57-56, Amanda Lassiter hit her third
3-pointer with just under five minutes left to play to give the
Lynx the lead for good.

Minnesota improved to 1-9 all-time in Houston.

Houston shot just 37 percent from the field, going 0-for-5 from
behind the arc.

Darling scored 10 second-half points for the Lynx, finishing
6-for-7 from the field.

"I came off screens and I was open for two or three seconds so
I had to shoot it," Darling said. "Once I start feeling it, there
is not turning back. I got focused and I just dominated."
